<h2>The question</h2>
<p>
  How much of the constellation's work must run <strong>isolated</strong> (a clone with its own HEAD, converging
  via <code>origin</code>) versus directly in the <strong>shared primary checkout</strong> — and what an
  automated closeout/integrator is allowed to touch. Triggered by a real incident where a parallel-batch closeout
  destroyed a concurrent session's in-progress work.
</p>

<h2>The incident (the evidence, not a hypothetical)</h2>
<p>
  In <code>batch-2026-06-29e</code>, a <code>/workflow</code> closeout ran in the <strong>shared</strong> primary
  checkout and diffed the <strong>dirty working tree</strong> to infer "its own residue." A concurrent
  <code>/prepare</code> session was at that moment authoring decision #1983 (status flip, a research topic, a
  report) — all uncommitted. Closeout mis-read that mid-flight state as batch residue and
  <code>git checkout</code>/<code>rm</code>'d it. No permanent loss <em>only by luck</em>. Crucially, the
  manifest <strong>already existed</strong> — the orchestrator records per-item <code>changedFiles</code> in its
  ledger and its central reconcile steps are read-only — so the bug is the <strong>method</strong>
  (dirty-tree-as-ownership), not a missing input.
</p>

<h2>Three rungs — three archetypes (the prep's reframe)</h2>
<p>
  The cold item framed one fork ("an escalation ladder; which rung, in what order"). The standing test splits it,
  and that split <em>is</em> the decision — bundling them would smuggle a scope-reopen past the incident's
  evidence. <strong>Resolved 2026-06-30</strong> (#1985): Rung 1 ratified as a forced invariant; Rung 2's
  <em>direction</em> ratified (adopt PR-flow / multi-session); Rung 3 folded into Rung 2's rollout mechanism,
  prepared as <strong>#1996</strong>.
</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Rung 1 — non-destructive, changeset-scoped closeout = a forced invariant.</strong> The excluded
    branch (infer ownership from the dirty tree) is <em>broken</em> — it destroyed real work. Act only on your own
    recorded manifest; never revert/delete a file you didn't write; never read <code>git status</code> as
    ownership. Terraform's "state is a snapshot, not live truth" (plan&rarr;apply enacts only the recorded diff)
    is the canonical prior art. <strong>Ratified.</strong></li>
  <li><strong>Rung 2 — operating model for the constellation's writers = a live operating-model fork; direction
    ratified: adopt PR-flow.</strong> Do the constellation's writers (agent <em>and</em> human sessions, not just
    <code>/workflow</code> batches) collaborate <em>through the remote</em> in a PR-flow (clone &rarr; push &rarr;
    gate &rarr; review &rarr; merge), or keep writing the shared primary checkout? This is <em>not</em> "settled by
    #1933": the incident alone doesn't justify it (Rung 1 removes the harm), so it stands on the stated
    <strong>multi-session operating-model goal</strong>, which deliberately supersedes #1933's solo-dev scope. The
    <code>lane/*</code> push transport already implements this and is the general primitive (reliable via #1995).
    <strong>Direction ratified — adopt PR-flow</strong>; the rollout mechanism (clone scope, per-lane dev-server
    ports, landing gate, branch protection) is prepared as its own decision, <strong>#1996</strong>.</li>
  <li><strong>Rung 3 — observe-only main for visual work = folds into Rung 2's mechanism (#1996).</strong>
    Observe-only main is the <em>end state</em> of PR-flow, so it is the visual-verification sub-question of the
    rollout mechanism, not a standalone call. Feasible institutionally (GitHub "require PR" / GitLab "push: no one"
    <em>are</em> observe-only main), but genuine per-lane <em>visual</em> rendering needs full clones with their
    own ports (worktrees give code isolation, not runtime isolation) plus the cross-origin WE+FUI wiring. It
    carries forward into #1996 as the per-lane visual harness (Gate 5), with its un-gate trigger intact: a
    <strong>falsifiable acceptance test</strong> — a lane reproduces the #1895 transparent-<code>.fui-card</code>
    regression and its fixed pass headlessly from the CLI.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Prior art (SE practice)</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>F1/F2</strong> — git worktrees share the object store/refs (only HEAD/index per-worktree) and
    refuse to check out a ref twice; a full clone avoids both (git-scm.com).</li>
  <li><strong>F3/F7</strong> — worktrees give code isolation, not <em>runtime</em> isolation (shared object
    store/DB can still corrupt) — <em>blog-level</em>. Why rung 3 needs clones+ports, not a branch.</li>
  <li><strong>F4/F5</strong> — trunk-based dev = short-lived single-owner branches converging via a review+CI
    gate (trunkbaseddevelopment.com, atlassian.com) — the map for <code>lane/*</code> as proto-PR units.</li>
  <li><strong>F8/F9/F10</strong> — GitHub branch protection / GitLab "Allowed to push: No one" <em>are</em> the
    institutional observe-only main (docs.github.com, docs.gitlab.com).</li>
  <li><strong>F11/F12</strong> — Terraform state is "a snapshot after the last apply, not a live representation";
    plan&rarr;apply enacts exactly the recorded diff, idempotently (developer.hashicorp.com) — exactly Rung 1.</li>
</ul>
